snippet.textDisplay: This song is from the region in Bengal where my parents grew up. A real song-of-the-earth. It was a barren and famine-filled area, but that's exactly what drove it to produce some of the most beautiful and goosebumps-inducing folk music I've ever heard.  Now viciously butchered by people who think that (frankly crappy) 21st century Bollywoodisation (or whatever crap this is) will somehow complement it. Feel like puking. Also Aditi is a total poser. The only addition I liked were the saxophones.

snippet.textDisplay:
Excellent Traditional Song, Music and atmosphere, but I & many think that the Rap is no way a part of traditional Folk-lore.
Just think of a North Indian Hindu Bride wearing Choorha, Mehandi, sindoor, mangal sutra etc, ...... But wearing Jeans or skirt.
Notice this compatibility difficulty issue in 'Zariya' where the Metal Pitcher ( Hang?) being played at 0:07 - 0:13 is not played (or is not audible) when Farah starts singing @4:30-4:50 in traditional arabic/gulf style, it is simply beacause the two rhythms do not match.
Similar situation in 'Dum Dum Andar' etc etc. 
The feedback/comments/criticisms may be respected and considered. 
Please avoid 'through glass'/blur video coverage.  

Rap in isolation/ separately is OK.
